And Quintilian says:

This doubling of the sound ol i, natural, even unavoid· able, between vowels, gives us the consonant effect (as vowel, uniting with the preceding, as consonant, introducing the following, vowel).

K has the same sound as in English.

The grammarians generally agree that k is a superfluous, or at least unnecessary, letter, its place being filled by c. Diomedes says:

[Keil. v. 1. pp. 423, 424] Ex his quibusdam supervacuae videntur k et q, quode littera harum locum possit implere.

And again : Κ consonans muta supervacua, qua utimur quando a correpta

sequitur, ut Kalendae, caput, calumniae.
